<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
Grumbuk-Dev wrote:<BR>I'll try to answer what I can.<BR><BR>weekly_ab_downage, the issue about chant agro was something in the top 10 list. This doesn't mean anything will be changed because it's in the top 10 list. Being in the top 10 list means that it's the top 10 things players want to see done. We do our best to change the game so that these items happen, because we want players to be happy with the game, but being in the list that players provide us isn't a promise it will be implemented. <BR>That said, I don't know what changed - if anything - related to chant kiting agro, but I can say that the changes that went in related to AA's should not have affected it. The only thing I can think of that might be a plausible explanation for code changes at that time affecting chant agro is perhaps the migration of AA's to a new system actually fixed a bug with Spell Casting Subtlety. It's not out of the question that it was bugged before, and perhaps isn't now. I can't think of anything else that might affect chant agro because as far as I know nobody made any changes directly to that song.<BR><BR>Thiberg, thanks for the clarification about it being more specific to chants. I think it's still a good idea to revisit the PBAE DoTs in order to give them the same amount of agro when the damage element is ignore due to movement, but that is a different issue as you point out. <BR><BR>Meresya, unfortunately there is a misunderstanding with what the top 10 lists are for. You describe the items in the top 10 as pending "fixes" when in fact they are things players would like changed because they think it would improve the game. They are in fact almost always feature requests with only an occasional legitimite bug. The designers may or may not agree with the changes, and when they don't, they aren't going to happen. That doesn't mean it's broken, it just means it's not what you think is how it should be. In my post above where I said "hate generation from DoT's was affected" I meant specifically, PBAE DoTs. This is because when the damage element is bypasses due to the PBAE changes, no damage related hate is generated for the PBAE dot. The change had no effect on any other song or spell, it was a very isolated and specific change. That is why I think it may be possible to identify how much hate would have been generated at that time and apply it to the hatelist - but it may not be as simple as that so I won't make any promises.&nbsp;<BR>
<P>Message Edited by Grumbuk-Dev on <SPAN class=date_text>12-11-2004</SPAN> <SPAN class=time_text>09:27 AM</SPAN><BR>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>First off, let me start by saying thanks for the response.&nbsp; It's Saturday, and I surely wasn't expecting your response so fast, if at all. <img src='/i/smilies/16x16_smiley-happy.gif' width=16 height=16 border=0>&nbsp; Secondly, my suggestion was on if the mobs wanted to move TO the bard, not away.&nbsp; And with your explanasion then it should still defeat the aoe kiting problem if everything else is left as is:&nbsp; Two bards, one has agro, so gets no dmg, nor any hate generation.&nbsp; Second bard can't sing aoe's until the first bard's songs drop.&nbsp; The second bard would tend to get agro at the same point as the first bard.&nbsp; While this might be doable by two very skilled bards, ping ponging the mobs in this fashion would be a lot harder, more time consuming, and excessively harder to macro, if at all possible.&nbsp; But point taken.</P>
<P>Actually, there isn't any confusion on the Top Ten List.&nbsp; The real confusion comes into play when countless bards have questioned the actual fizzle rates just over the past five months, not counting prior postings on the same showing how the implimentation of fizzles as applied to bards is excessive even by caster standards, yet it's still being looked into at this time.&nbsp; This above all else is the thorn in every single player of the bard class.&nbsp; Casters got a workaround via socials for almost all of their fizzle problems.&nbsp; Bards can't do this because of the nature of twisting.&nbsp; Casters of comparable level have spells with durations of an hour up to almost four hours.&nbsp; The longest song duration is two and a half minutes for a bard, but generally a bard is chain casting three to four song, and constantly reapplying them, or altering them, but in essence, twisting three to four songs almost constantly for hours on end.&nbsp; My cleric is only 62nd level, and has never fizzled tens time in a gaming session.&nbsp; Add to this the UI work around, and she may get one string of multiple fizzles that truly effect game play.&nbsp; I'm at present a level 67th bard, with all the AA fizzle and recover aas maxed, maxed stats on all at 325 except&nbsp;wisdom, and have numerous logs showing fizzle counts in the hundreds, casting up to 4000 a session, recovers only up to the single digits.&nbsp; Logs show a fizzle rate average of one fizzle every four minutes.</P>
<P>SOE may consider this as something minor, but most bards do not.&nbsp; Some have plain outright quit because of it.&nbsp; Others simply quit playing a bard.&nbsp; A bard already has to pay more attention to detail within the game and within the spectrum of casting just to be the best they can be than any other class in the game.&nbsp; To also be the only class to have to pay good aa points just to attain a mediocrum of less fizzles than what is normal, adding in already being socially challenged, and the sheer frustration over the entire implimentation.... I don't consider it a wish list item.&nbsp; I consider it a bug, or at the other end, an excessively high cost pkysically, mentally, emotionally, as well as being overly constraining for a game that is supposed to be above all else, FUN.</P>
<P>Just to provide real data:</P>
<P>Group song:&nbsp; 2,257 casts&nbsp; Target&nbsp;songs (on players) 6 casts&nbsp; NPS songs (mobs) 302 casts = 2, 565 total casts.&nbsp; Game session 9 hours.&nbsp; Fizzles 66, Recovered fizzles 17. Fizzle average one fizzle every 8.18 minutes.&nbsp; Fizzle Recovery&nbsp; 25.75%&nbsp; </P>
<P>Addition mathematics:</P>
<P>A caster casts 100 spells in an hour (personally Id have to see logs to believe the amount of casts).&nbsp; Fizzle rate is 5%, so the caster can fizzle five times in an hour.&nbsp; This yields a possible fizzle rate average of one every 12 minutes.&nbsp; My log: 9 hours played, 4, 224 casts, 111 fizzles, for a fizzle rate of one every 5.225 minutes.&nbsp; This is a fizzle rate of 2.62%, after AAs.&nbsp; This is 2.297 times higher in time duration than casters, as well as just over half a caster's fizzle rate.&nbsp; This shows bards pay a higher price on fizzles than casters due because the formula doesn't include duration, the one thing casters have inherent in their spells, of which bards do not.&nbsp; Add in social workarounds for casting classes and you have ultra rare game effecting effects due to actual player attentiveness for casters.&nbsp; This doesn't even include like level casters, and all that would or could come with it.</P>
<P>Bottom line is that I feel it is a bug, This is all based on my own logs, with all the AAs.&nbsp; I don't have the the two level specific AAs because the songs fizzling are not covered by them anyway.&nbsp; Although now bards are reporting that the second one is bugged, effecting all fizzles regardless of song level.&nbsp; While I'd love to buy it for that, SOE would just fix the bug, causing me to waste another 30 AAs on something with no inherent value to me at my current level of play.</P>
<P>And lastly:&nbsp; Every other class has gotten alterations from things listed in their top ten list, except bards so far.&nbsp; We've had to wait over five months for one single thing, and that is only happening because you did the coding on your own time.&nbsp; So I'm saying it isn't like bards are asking for cheals, ports, or anything totally outrageous.&nbsp; Also, almost all of the items have been in a being evaluated classification since day one of the list.&nbsp; Yet bards have been mostly ignored, or told four months later that nothing was known about something while it was right there on the lists.&nbsp; In a nutshell, we see other classes getting things asked for, and we see us being mostly ignored for over four months.&nbsp; The boards were opened back up to facilitate communication.&nbsp; How can it be called communication when bards feel they are mostly talking to themselves?&nbsp; This is why I was shocked to see your response.&nbsp; Yes, shocked is the right word, albeit maybe a little conservative.</P>
<P>Polara<BR></P></DIV>
																		
